<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,324,1910,1936]" box="[189,324,1910,1936]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1910,1936]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1910,1936]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,1399,1956,2018]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
The species name, a noun in apposition, was formed by combining the Greek prefix ʻ 
<emphasis box="[1218,1265,1956,1982]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">cycl</emphasis>
-ʼ (ʻcircleʼ) with ʻ- 
<emphasis box="[268,309,1992,2017]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">ura</emphasis>
ʼ (ʻtailʼ), referring to the shape of the aedeagus in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
